spec: decimal_extra1531
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(decimal)
docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/decimal.html
provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/decimal.html — decimal module Decimal, Context, DecimalException, InvalidOperation documentation"
    - "IBM General Decimal Arithmetic Specification, Version 1.72 — comparison operator semantics"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-12"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "CPython source: Modules/_decimal/_decimal.c"
    - "CPython source: Lib/_pydecimal.py"
    - "decimal.zspec.zsdl — covers arithmetic operations and basic Decimal usage"
    - "decimal_extra.zspec.zsdl — covers predicates (is_nan, is_infinite, is_zero, is_signed), to_eng_string, Context/BasicContext/ExtendedContext class names, rounding mode constants"
    - "decimal_extra1516.zspec.zsdl — covers arithmetic/numeric operator presence (wave 548)"
  notes:
    - "Wave 549 (_extra1531): comparison operator __dict__ presence checks for decimal module classes."
    - "decimal.Decimal defines ALL seven comparison operators in its own __dict__: __lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __ne__, __eq__, __hash__. Decimal implements the full IEEE 754 comparison operator set with proper NaN handling."
    - "decimal.Decimal comparison operators follow IEEE 754 semantics: NaN comparisons return False for all ordering operators and raise InvalidOperation; Decimal('NaN') == Decimal('NaN') is False."
    - "__hash__ is defined consistently with __eq__: equal Decimal values have equal hashes; Decimal('1.0') != Decimal('1.00') so they may have different hashes (trailing zeros are significant)."
    - "decimal.Context does NOT define any comparison operators in its own __dict__. Context instances are configuration objects, not ordered value types."
    - "decimal.DecimalException and decimal.InvalidOperation are exception classes with minimal __dict__ entries; they define no comparison operators."
    - "decimal.Decimal and re.Pattern are the only two classes in the wave 549 survey that define all seven comparison operators (__lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __ne__, __eq__, __hash__) in their own __dict__."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-12."
  created_at: "2026-04-12T00:00:00Z"
error_model: python_exceptions

table decimal_extra1531.decimal_comparison_ops_present:
  description: "decimal.Decimal comparison operator presence — __lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __ne__, __eq__, __hash__ are all defined in decimal.Decimal.__dict__; Decimal implements the full IEEE 754 comparison protocol including NaN-safe semantics; wave 549"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: comparison_ops
  id_prefix: dc1531dc
  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [dc1531dc001,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__lt__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__lt__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __lt__ in its own __dict__; Decimal < Decimal implements IEEE 754 decimal less-than comparison; Decimal('1') < Decimal('2') is True; NaN comparisons return False: Decimal('NaN') < Decimal('1') is False; __lt__ is one of all seven comparison operators defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc002,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__le__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__le__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __le__ in its own __dict__; Decimal <= Decimal implements IEEE 754 less-than-or-equal comparison; Decimal('1') <= Decimal('1') is True; __le__ and __lt__ together enable sorted() and bisect on Decimal sequences; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc003,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__gt__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__gt__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __gt__ in its own __dict__; Decimal > Decimal implements IEEE 754 greater-than comparison; Decimal('2') > Decimal('1') is True; all four ordering operators (__lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__) are defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc004,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__ge__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__ge__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __ge__ in its own __dict__; Decimal >= Decimal implements IEEE 754 greater-than-or-equal comparison; __ge__ completes the four-operator ordering set; Decimal ordering respects sign, magnitude, and exponent under IEEE 754 rules; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc005,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__eq__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__eq__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __eq__ in its own __dict__; Decimal equality is value-based: Decimal('1.0') == Decimal('1.0') is True; IEEE 754 NaN semantics apply: Decimal('NaN') == Decimal('NaN') is False (NaN is not equal to anything including itself); __eq__ is defined alongside __hash__ to maintain hash consistency; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc006,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__hash__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__hash__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __hash__ in its own __dict__; Decimal objects are hashable and can be used as dict keys; __hash__ is consistent with __eq__: equal Decimal values have equal hashes; Decimal('1') == 1 (int equality) so hash(Decimal('1')) == hash(1); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc007,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__ne__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__ne__') == True — decimal.Decimal explicitly defines __ne__ in its own __dict__; not-equal comparison is explicitly defined rather than relying on the default negation of __eq__; this matches re.Pattern (which also explicitly defines __ne__) and contrasts with pathlib.PurePath (which omits __ne__ and uses the inherited default); all seven comparison-protocol members are defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc008,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__add__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__add__') == True — positive cross-wave anchor: Decimal.__dict__ contains both arithmetic operators (wave 548: __add__, __sub__, __mul__, etc.) and comparison operators (wave 549: __lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __ne__, __eq__, __hash__); Decimal is the most protocol-complete class in the wave 549 survey, defining all seven comparison operators alongside all seventeen arithmetic operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531dc009,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__lt__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__lt__') == True — wave 549 summary anchor: decimal.Decimal defines all seven comparison operators (__lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __ne__, __eq__, __hash__) in its own __dict__; it is one of only two classes in the four-module wave 549 survey (alongside re.Pattern) that defines the complete comparison protocol; pathlib.PurePath defines six (missing __ne__); all io classes define zero; all re.Match/re.error/decimal.Context/decimal.DecimalException define zero; verified with Python 3.14.3"]

table decimal_extra1531.context_comparison_ops_absent:
  description: "decimal.Context comparison operator absence — __lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __ne__, __eq__, __hash__ are all absent from decimal.Context.__dict__; Context is a configuration object for decimal arithmetic precision and rounding, not an ordered value type; positive anchors show __init__ and prec ARE present; wave 549"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: comparison_ops
  id_prefix: dc1531cx
  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [dc1531cx001,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__lt__"],
       false,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__lt__') == False — decimal.Context is a configuration object specifying precision, rounding mode, and trap enablers for decimal arithmetic; it is not an ordered value type; __lt__ is absent from Context.__dict__; Context instances cannot be compared for ordering; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx002,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__le__"],
       false,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__le__') == False — decimal.Context does not define __le__ in its own __dict__; less-than-or-equal comparison is meaningless for arithmetic context objects; Context defines numeric methods (add, multiply, divide) but no comparison operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx003,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__gt__"],
       false,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__gt__') == False — decimal.Context does not define __gt__ in its own __dict__; greater-than comparison is not part of the Context protocol; the four ordering operators are all absent from Context.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx004,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__ge__"],
       false,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__ge__') == False — decimal.Context does not define __ge__ in its own __dict__; the complete ordering operator set (__lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__) is absent from Context.__dict__; contrast with decimal.Decimal which defines all four ordering operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx005,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__eq__"],
       false,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__eq__') == False — decimal.Context does not define __eq__ in its own __dict__; equality comparison uses the default object identity semantics inherited from object; two Context objects with identical precision and rounding are not equal unless they are the same object; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx006,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__hash__"],
       false,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__hash__') == False — decimal.Context does not define __hash__ in its own __dict__; hashing uses the default identity-based hash; Context instances are not hashable by their configuration values; contrast with decimal.Decimal which defines __hash__ for use in sets and dicts; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx007,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__ne__"],
       false,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__ne__') == False — decimal.Context does not define __ne__ in its own __dict__; the complete comparison set (__lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __eq__, __ne__, __hash__) is absent from Context.__dict__; this mirrors io classes and re.Match; the contrast with decimal.Decimal (which defines all seven) highlights that comparison operators are a feature of the Decimal value type, not the Context configuration object; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx008,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__init__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('__init__') == True — positive anchor: decimal.Context defines '__init__' in its own __dict__; Context objects are configurable and have a substantive __init__ that accepts precision, rounding, and trap arguments; the class dict contains configuration and arithmetic methods, not comparison operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531cx009,
       decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["prec"],
       true,
       "decimal.Context.__dict__.__contains__('prec') == True — positive anchor: decimal.Context defines 'prec' as a descriptor in its own __dict__; the prec descriptor controls the precision (number of significant digits) for Decimal arithmetic operations; Context.__dict__ contains attribute descriptors (prec, rounding, Emax, Emin, clamp) and numeric methods (add, subtract, multiply, divide) but no comparison operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]

table decimal_extra1531.exception_comparison_ops_absent:
  description: "decimal.DecimalException and decimal.InvalidOperation comparison operator absence — all seven comparison operators absent from both exception classes; exception classes have minimal __dict__ entries; wave 549"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: comparison_ops
  id_prefix: dc1531ex
  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [dc1531ex001,
       decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__lt__"],
       false,
       "decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__('__lt__') == False — decimal.DecimalException is the base exception class for all decimal arithmetic exceptions; it inherits from ArithmeticError and Exception; its __dict__ is minimal (__module__, __weakref__, __doc__) with no comparison operators; exception classes do not define ordering operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex002,
       decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__eq__"],
       false,
       "decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__('__eq__') == False — decimal.DecimalException does not define __eq__ in its own __dict__; equality comparison uses the default object identity semantics inherited from object; exception instances are compared by identity, not by their exception type or message; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex003,
       decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__hash__"],
       false,
       "decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__('__hash__') == False — decimal.DecimalException does not define __hash__ in its own __dict__; hashing uses the default identity-based hash; exception instances are not hashable by their content; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex004,
       decimal.InvalidOperation.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__lt__"],
       false,
       "decimal.InvalidOperation.__dict__.__contains__('__lt__') == False — decimal.InvalidOperation is the exception raised for invalid Decimal operations (e.g., Decimal('NaN') < Decimal('1') with traps enabled); it inherits from DecimalException and ArithmeticError; its __dict__ is minimal with no comparison operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex005,
       decimal.InvalidOperation.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__eq__"],
       false,
       "decimal.InvalidOperation.__dict__.__contains__('__eq__') == False — decimal.InvalidOperation does not define __eq__ in its own __dict__; equality uses default object identity; InvalidOperation instances are not comparable by content; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex006,
       decimal.InvalidOperation.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__hash__"],
       false,
       "decimal.InvalidOperation.__dict__.__contains__('__hash__') == False — decimal.InvalidOperation does not define __hash__ in its own __dict__; hashing uses the default identity-based hash; wave 549 summary for decimal: Decimal defines all seven comparison operators; Context defines none; DecimalException defines none; InvalidOperation defines none; only the Decimal value type implements the comparison protocol; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex007,
       decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__le__"],
       false,
       "decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__('__le__') == False — decimal.DecimalException does not define __le__ in its own __dict__; the complete ordering set (__lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__) is absent; exception classes in the decimal module (DecimalException, InvalidOperation, DivisionByZero, Overflow, Underflow) do not define any comparison operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex008,
       decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__gt__"],
       false,
       "decimal.DecimalException.__dict__.__contains__('__gt__') == False — decimal.DecimalException does not define __gt__ in its own __dict__; greater-than comparison is not part of the exception protocol; exception classes inherit ordering from object (no total ordering); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1531ex009,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__eq__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__eq__') == True — cross-class summary anchor: decimal.Decimal defines __eq__ in its own __dict__ while decimal.DecimalException and decimal.InvalidOperation do not; this confirms that comparison operators are a property of the Decimal value type, not of the exception classes in the decimal module; wave 549 final result for decimal: Decimal defines all seven (__lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __ne__, __eq__, __hash__); Context, DecimalException, and InvalidOperation define zero; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
